These things being granted, we assert that the diaphragm in its contractiori is moved towards a plane, in other words, when it contracts, it goes towards the cavity ol the abdomen, that is, outwards and downwards. For ir is known from anatomical observation that the form of the diaphragm is curved, and that its concave surface or sinus looks towards the belly; but now as any curved surlace whatsoever moves, in contracting, towards a plane, that is, towards ¹ the region to which its concave surface looks, and as the parts of the abdomen to which the concave surface of the diaphragm looks are relatively to it, inferior and exterior, it necessarily follows that when the diaphragm, in its contractiori, moves towards them, in its contracted state it goes downwards and outwards. And besides, this can be seen in vivi· sections by simple inspection. In this connection I am much astonished that the eminent Dr Willis, in his Answer to Dr Highmore, ‘has expressed the opinion, “ That the diaphragm in violent inspiration, such as sometimes occurs in the case ol dying persons, descends beyond the plane and becomes very convex towards the intestines.'’ For this does not seem very likely: ior it is not “possible that such a descent of the diaphragm should be caused by the lungs taking a long inspiration,'' as the distinguished author supposed, inasmuch as the inspiration and the swelling of the lungs are caused by the descent os the diaphragm and the dilatation of the chest.
